results.title: Pleuro
results.creator_credit: Jack Keane, Ann Millard and Victoria. Dept. of Agriculture
results.brief_description:
Film made to alert farmers of Pleuro-Pneoumonia, a nothern-state illness that could cripple local cattle if it was introduced into Victoria. Details how the illness manifests itself in cattle, its symptoms and how it is treated. Also describes the process of quarantine if Pleuro is suspected.

Uses diagramatical animations and illustrations throughout. These feature an animated map of Australia and Victoria. Numerous shots of cattle in hot and dry conditions. Amongst other bloody imagery there is footage of organs being removed from diseased cow and placed in a tin. Nice cheesey sequence of quarantine signs being placed around a property. Good ‘The End’ title.

results.title: 1957 Pig Carcase Competition
results.brief_description: Details and promotes the 1957 Pig Carcase competition as well as pork production in Victoria as a whole. Similar to the 1955 Pig Carcase competition in format and style. Includes various shots of carcases being cut for display, general crowd shots, an awards ceremony and a speech by an official. Features fantastic footage of three carcases hanging up in front of a black backdrop being inspected and caressed by a man. Nice theatrical quality to it. Excellent shot of a boy inspecting pork shot from behind, highlighting very cute jeans. End of piece features an official from the Board of Meat, aided by illustrations, talking about how pork production in Victoria has improved over time. Behind him hang carcases and behind them there is a red wall. He wears a pink and red tie. This creates a quirky, very good-looking frame of man, meat and pig illustration. Soundtrack features music of the period and earnest narration about ‘pig raisers’.

results.title: May 1955 pig carcase competition
results.brief_description:
Propaganda piece highlighting Victoria’s development as the foremost producer of pork in Australia. Competition received a record number of entries and the winning score of 93/100 for a carcase was the highest total ever in Australia. Winner was a ‘new Australian’ from Italy.

The cracases are beautifully displayed and almost fetishised as if in an art gallery. Everyone involved takes great joy, interest and pride in the meat displayed to an amusingly earnest extent. The images are high-contrast with vibrant reds and greens. A combination of the above provides a beautifully surreal quality to the piece.

Amusing sound grabs from narration such as “Here we have a veritable paradise of pork”.

Interesting ‘The End’ illustration, good for Postcards, etc.

results.title: Taming the red swamp
results.brief_description: Vision only. Film seems to be about the techniques employed to make waterlogged land usable for crops. Footage includes old-style farm vehicles and machinery being used to achieve this. Nice shot of 6 new red tractors driving through the terrain. Also features an amusing moment where two men push a large poll into the ground to prove how soft the soil is. General shots of cattle are scattered throughout. Nice, kitsch begining and end illustrated titles. Good ‘The End’, possibly for postcard.

results.title: Agricultural Collection
results.brief_description:
From the 1940s, the Department of Agriculture’s Film and Video Unit produced film and later video. When this unit was closed, the film and video masters and raw footage were passed to Agmedia. Agmedia produced a range of videos, principally on behalf of the Department until 1996 when it was closed. Ownership of its films and videos (including copyright) reverted to the Department of Natural Resources and Environment (the successor agency to the Department of Agriculture).
The Department of Agriculture’s Head Office Library also operated a film lending service. This was closed in 1993 and their collection of 200+ 16mm films plus videos was placed in storage.
In 1997, following the relocation of the DRNE, the collection was passed to Cinemedia for short-term storage (in controlled atmosphere) for a nominal fee. The collection consisting of 1804 film titles and over 2,000 videos, included:
· The pre 1990 Film and Video Unit master tapes and raw footage;
· The Agmedia masters and raw footage (around 750 films and tapes); and
· The library collection of 16mm films and videos
From many perspectives, this is an important collection, not just because it records Victoria’s agricultural heritage, but also because many of our filmmakers learnt their craft in making these films. There are treasures to be uncovered in the camera original footage.

results.title: A Crop of records
results.brief_description: In 1960, Victoria’s wheat growing record was smashed by a bumper harvest. 95% of the wheat was from varieties bred by the Victorian Department of Agriculture including Pinnacle; Insignia; Beacon; and Olympic. Don Rooney, an agronomist in the Wimmera region talks to Victorian farmer Harry Bouchier about his record harvest. We follow the wheat’s journey from the farm, to the silos and finally being loaded onto cargo ships at the Port of Geelong headed for international destinations.

results.title: The Argentine ant
results.brief_description: This film describes the methods used by State and Municipal authorities and C.S.I.R.O. to eradicate the Argentine Ant in large suburban and city areas. The efforts of individual householders to eradicate the pest have proved unsuccessful. The film shows, in detail, the large scale methods developed by the C.S.I.R.O. which have been used systematically and methodically in attempting to eradicate the pest.

results.title: Songlines in the city. Episode 1
results.creator_credit: SKA TV, Rob Nairn, Fiona Dean, Campbell Manderson, Grant Hansen, Glen Edwards and Peter Lane
results.brief_description:
The Shows Songlines in the City is hosted by two of Melbourne’s Indigenous Musicians, Kutcha Edwards and Grant Hansen, both former members of well known Indigenous rock act Blackfire, and radio stalwarts at local community radio station 3CR.
The three shows have a magazine format with interviews and performances with some of Australia’s leading Aboriginal and non-indigenous artists, including Richard Frankland, Lou Bennet, Andy Alberts, Deniece Hudson, Paul Hester and Nick Barker. All the artists appearing on the show are involved with the Songlines Aboriginal Music Corporation Mentorship Program.
Actors, filmmakers and community members are also profiled. Segments include ‘Kids Talk’ at a local Aboriginal child-care centre, and a chat with koori students involved in an innovative education program
Episode One includes performances by Deniece Hudson with Nick Barker, and Kutcha and Grant with Paul Hester. It also includes the Kids Talk segment, Kate Munroe with the koori news, and interviews.
Community Context
‘Songlines in the City, Episode One’ is one of three half hour shows shot as a pilot for an ongoing indigenous series on Community Television Station Channel 31, Melbourne.
In 2001, SKA TV (a Community Television Production Group) approached Kutcha and Grant with the idea of a local indigenous TV show. SKA applied for and received $2500 from the City of Darebin to assist in the production of the pilots.
Community TV Production Groups RMITV and SKA TV provided in-kind assistance with equipment, facilities and crews, and produced the shows together with Kutcha, Grant, and Fiona Dean.
As a result of this mentoring project, the Aboriginal community received training funding to continue Songlines in the City as an ongoing Victorian koori show in 2002 on Channel 31, Melbourne.

results.title: Cinema
results.brief_description: Sebastian C. Schroeder’s sublime 1973 film ‘Cinema’, takes the physicality of film itself as a site of transformation, as celluloid itself metamorphoses into a magical realm for a group of Afghani children.
